Thank you.

00:00:46.160 --> 00:00:46.826
I appreciate it.

00:00:50.100 --> 00:00:53.000
Good morning.

00:00:53.000 --> 00:00:55.100
I apologize for being
late, but it is entirely

00:00:55.100 --> 00:01:00.520
your Queen's fault. The book
is called "When to Rob a Bank,"

00:01:00.520 --> 00:01:02.290
which is almost entirely random.

00:01:02.290 --> 00:01:06.060
So if you really want to know
more about how to do that,

00:01:06.060 --> 00:01:07.880
I can tell you.

00:01:07.880 --> 00:01:09.630
Although the short
answer is "don't."

00:01:09.630 --> 00:01:11.150
The ROI on bank
robbery is terrible.

00:01:11.150 --> 00:01:12.530
That's what it's
really all about.

00:01:12.530 --> 00:01:14.560
It's actually a story of how
the book came to be called

00:01:14.560 --> 00:01:15.643
what it came to be called.

00:01:15.643 --> 00:01:17.850
So if we want to get
into that later in Q&amp;A,

00:01:17.850 --> 00:01:20.146
we can, which is how little
leverage authors exert

00:01:20.146 --> 00:01:21.770
with their publishers
even when they've

00:01:21.770 --> 00:01:22.936
sold a few copies of a book.

00:01:22.936 --> 00:01:25.250
Because that was our
third or fourth title.

00:01:25.250 --> 00:01:26.510
The first few got rejected.

00:01:26.510 --> 00:01:30.450
So anyway, there is a book
called "When to Rob a Bank."

00:01:30.450 --> 00:01:33.370
It is a book that
is a compilation

00:01:33.370 --> 00:01:37.270
of the best, the greatest hits,
of our blog from 10 years.

00:01:37.270 --> 00:01:40.770
So we published by now
about 8,500 blog posts

00:01:40.770 --> 00:01:43.050
over the course of 10
years, most of which

00:01:43.050 --> 00:01:47.200
were terrible either in
the moment or beyond.

00:01:47.200 --> 00:01:48.359
They just didn't last.

00:01:48.359 --> 00:01:50.150
But we went through,
and we found about 500

00:01:50.150 --> 00:01:51.774
that we actually
still enjoyed reading.

00:01:51.774 --> 00:01:53.512
Then we whittled
that down to 132.

00:01:53.512 --> 00:01:54.720
So that's what's in the book.

00:01:54.720 --> 00:01:56.972
So I'm gonna talk for a while.

00:01:56.972 --> 00:01:58.430
Then I'll take
questions, because I

00:01:58.430 --> 00:02:00.380
know every time I speak
at a Google event,

00:02:00.380 --> 00:02:02.050
there are a lot of questions
which I really enjoy.

00:02:02.050 --> 00:02:03.760
So I'm not gonna talk
too long right now.

00:02:03.760 --> 00:02:08.340
But the occasion of the
book was the 10 year

00:02:08.340 --> 00:02:10.475
anniversary of the
publication of our first book,

00:02:10.475 --> 00:02:11.100
"Freakonomics."

00:02:11.100 --> 00:02:13.190
So this is our fourth
book, and for 10 years,

00:02:13.190 --> 00:02:15.370
I've been working together
with Steve Levitt, who's

00:02:15.370 --> 00:02:17.119
an economist at the
University of Chicago.

00:02:17.119 --> 00:02:20.077
And we've been doing
this project together

00:02:20.077 --> 00:02:21.410
that's had many different forms.

00:02:21.410 --> 00:02:23.890
The first couple
books were, largely

00:02:23.890 --> 00:02:26.520
but not exclusively, based on
academic research he'd done.

00:02:26.520 --> 00:02:28.728
Our third book was called
"Think Like a Freak," which

00:02:28.728 --> 00:02:31.310
was using everything
we'd learned

00:02:31.310 --> 00:02:33.710
from not only methodology
but from getting out

00:02:33.710 --> 00:02:36.750
in the real world to work
with firms and governments

00:02:36.750 --> 00:02:37.990
to try to solve problems.

00:02:37.990 --> 00:02:39.180
Because after the
first couple books,

00:02:39.180 --> 00:02:40.804
we were called in by
people who thought

00:02:40.804 --> 00:02:43.000
we'd be useful in that way.

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:45.550
Almost always we
weren't, but we set

00:02:45.550 --> 00:02:47.709
out a blueprint for problem
solving, essentially.

00:02:47.709 --> 00:02:49.500
And then this fourth
book, which as I said,

00:02:49.500 --> 00:02:53.150
is a compilation of blog
posts marking 10 years

00:02:53.150 --> 00:02:55.160
of us doing our thing together.

00:02:55.160 --> 00:03:02.490
So it is inherently
a retrospective time.

00:03:02.490 --> 00:03:04.430
As all anniversaries are.

00:03:04.430 --> 00:03:08.850
And because we've been doing a
long time you start to think--

00:03:08.850 --> 00:03:11.660
or I've started to think--
a little bit about legacy,

00:03:11.660 --> 00:03:16.660
and what it means to do anything
for that long a time, and what

00:03:16.660 --> 00:03:19.620
kind of mark if any one leaves.

00:03:19.620 --> 00:03:22.580
And so I wanted
to share with you,

00:03:22.580 --> 00:03:24.360
I think, the
perfect illustration

00:03:24.360 --> 00:03:28.590
of the legacy of "Freakonomics"
as gleaned last night.

00:03:28.590 --> 00:03:31.725
When I was here in London I was
doing media all day yesterday.

00:03:31.725 --> 00:03:37.900
It started about 8:00 AM, and
it went till about 11:30 PM,

00:03:37.900 --> 00:03:38.560
right?

00:03:38.560 --> 00:03:43.411
And the last stop was the
500th BBC visit of the day,

00:03:43.411 --> 00:03:44.410
and it was "News Night."

00:03:44.410 --> 00:03:45.868
So does anybody
watch "News Night?"

00:03:45.868 --> 00:03:46.820
I assume not, really.

00:03:49.500 --> 00:03:53.420
So I'm in the green room
at "News Night," which

00:03:53.420 --> 00:03:57.620
is the room where they put
the guests before they go on.

00:03:57.620 --> 00:04:02.500
And there were a couple
of MPs, male MPs who--

00:04:02.500 --> 00:04:05.930
one conservative, one liberal,
or whatever you call them,

00:04:05.930 --> 00:04:07.666
Labour-- and

00:04:07.666 --> 00:04:09.600
[LAUGHTER]

00:04:09.600 --> 00:04:13.310
They were and they
were just chatting

00:04:13.310 --> 00:04:14.720
very amiably with each other.

00:04:14.720 --> 00:04:19.260
And then they got ushered in to
the set to go do their piece.

00:04:19.260 --> 00:04:22.510
And then someone else
came in, and this

00:04:22.510 --> 00:04:24.260
was a woman who was also an MP.

00:04:24.260 --> 00:04:27.810
And she's standing now for
the head of Labour Party.

00:04:27.810 --> 00:04:30.800
So I probably shouldn't
name her because

00:04:30.800 --> 00:04:34.365
of what I'm about to tell
you about what she said,

00:04:34.365 --> 00:04:35.490
although it's not that bad.

00:04:35.490 --> 00:04:37.490
And I understand there
are three women running?

00:04:37.490 --> 00:04:39.680
So you'd have to actually go
back and watch last night's

00:04:39.680 --> 00:04:40.680
show to narrow it down.

00:04:40.680 --> 00:04:42.388
So I'm not going to
do that work for you.

00:04:42.388 --> 00:04:48.200
But one of the three women
who were standing for Labour,

00:04:48.200 --> 00:04:50.970
you could tell right away she's
a great politician because she

00:04:50.970 --> 00:04:54.044
looks at us, and she
wants to know who we are,

00:04:54.044 --> 00:04:55.710
what we're doing,
very friendly, chatty,

00:04:55.710 --> 00:04:57.001
sticking out her hand to shake.

00:04:57.001 --> 00:04:58.830
She has her bike
helmet, which I'm

00:04:58.830 --> 00:05:03.240
sure she brought along with
her in the taxi to look good.

00:05:03.240 --> 00:05:06.160
And she says what
are you in for?

00:05:06.160 --> 00:05:08.660
That's what they always ask you
when you're in a green room.

00:05:08.660 --> 00:05:10.110
And I always say
homicide, because that's

00:05:10.110 --> 00:05:11.910
what they ask in my country when
they say what are you in jail

00:05:11.910 --> 00:05:12.430
for.

00:05:12.430 --> 00:05:14.587
So then she said, what
are you gonna talk about?

00:05:14.587 --> 00:05:15.670
And I said, I'm an author.

00:05:15.670 --> 00:05:16.860
I'm gonna talk about the books.

00:05:16.860 --> 00:05:17.693
She said what books?

00:05:17.693 --> 00:05:20.940
And I said, I write
the "Freakomics" books.

00:05:20.940 --> 00:05:23.700
And she said oh, oh.

00:05:23.700 --> 00:05:25.040
And she starts nodding.

00:05:25.040 --> 00:05:26.950
And she said, yeah.

00:05:26.950 --> 00:05:29.920
I've loved-- I remember
reading "Freakonomics."

00:05:29.920 --> 00:05:33.580
She said that was the book
with the ridiculous names like

00:05:33.580 --> 00:05:36.900
Shithead that's pronounced
"Shuh-teed," right?

00:05:36.900 --> 00:05:38.500
And I said, yeah, yeah.

00:05:38.500 --> 00:05:41.360
And this is what the MP who's
running for head of Labour

00:05:41.360 --> 00:05:43.560
remembers about the book, right?

00:05:43.560 --> 00:05:45.150
She says, oh, yeah, Shithead.

00:05:45.150 --> 00:05:46.250
I loved Shithead.

00:05:46.250 --> 00:05:47.600
That was fantastic.

00:05:47.600 --> 00:05:50.200
So it's not about any of
the public policy stuff.

00:05:50.200 --> 00:05:52.490
It's not about the relationship
of abortion and crime.

00:05:52.490 --> 00:05:53.680
It's not about drug dealing.

00:05:53.680 --> 00:05:54.680
It's not about anything.

00:05:54.680 --> 00:05:55.520
It's Shithead.

00:05:55.520 --> 00:05:57.810
And then furthermore,
she says, yeah,

00:05:57.810 --> 00:06:00.210
I really love how you
wrote that when parents

00:06:00.210 --> 00:06:01.940
give their kids these
ridiculous names,

00:06:01.940 --> 00:06:03.987
they ruin their lives for them.

00:06:03.987 --> 00:06:05.820
And what I wanted to
say, what I always want

00:06:05.820 --> 00:06:07.361
to say in that
situation but never do

00:06:07.361 --> 00:06:09.810
is that, actually, you've
got that exactly wrong.

00:06:09.810 --> 00:06:12.440
The argument that we made
using the data on naming,

00:06:12.440 --> 00:06:15.280
and parents education, and the
outcome of children, and so on

00:06:15.280 --> 00:06:17.030
was that the name that
you give your child

00:06:17.030 --> 00:06:18.295
doesn't matter at all.

00:06:18.295 --> 00:06:21.740
All the name is is an indicator
of who the parents are.

00:06:21.740 --> 00:06:26.410
But if your Parents A, and
you have a boy named James,

00:06:26.410 --> 00:06:28.590
or parents B and your
observationally equivalent

00:06:28.590 --> 00:06:32.230
to Parents A, and you name your
boy Shithead-- or "Shuh-teed"--

00:06:32.230 --> 00:06:34.900
Shithead and James are not
going to have any substantially

00:06:34.900 --> 00:06:36.233
different outcome in their life.

00:06:36.233 --> 00:06:38.150
That's what the data
showed, and yet,

00:06:38.150 --> 00:06:40.650
most people who read
this and remember,

00:06:40.650 --> 00:06:43.570
remember exactly wrong.

00:06:43.570 --> 00:06:47.460
So the two things that the
potential ahead of Labour Party

00:06:47.460 --> 00:06:52.280
remembers about our legacy is
Shithead, and she got it wrong.

00:06:52.280 --> 00:06:56.520
So that's my legacy.

00:06:56.520 --> 00:06:59.510
That's what I'll be
remembered for, if anything.

00:06:59.510 --> 00:07:02.430
And I guess it's deserving.

00:07:02.430 --> 00:07:06.210
Because let me tell you
know how I spend my day.

00:07:06.210 --> 00:07:08.397
So I know you all
are mostly engineers?

00:07:08.397 --> 00:07:08.980
All engineers?

00:07:08.980 --> 00:07:10.170
Anybody here not an engineer?

00:07:10.170 --> 00:07:10.860
Anybody sneak in?

00:07:10.860 --> 00:07:11.900
Where did you sneak in from?

00:07:11.900 --> 00:07:12.140
Yeah.

00:07:12.140 --> 00:07:13.390
Are you in the building?

00:07:13.390 --> 00:07:14.860
[LAUGHTER]

00:07:14.860 --> 00:07:16.820
AUDIENCE: So I'm not
even in this building.

00:07:16.820 --> 00:07:18.996
I'm in our sales
office, but I managed

00:07:18.996 --> 00:07:20.246
to sneak in from another door.

00:07:20.246 --> 00:07:20.630
STEVEN J. DUBNER: OK.

00:07:20.630 --> 00:07:23.260
That's why you have such better
glasses than the engineers.

00:07:23.260 --> 00:07:24.675
[LAUGHTER]

00:07:24.675 --> 00:07:25.800
There were a couple others.

00:07:25.800 --> 00:07:26.750
Are you?

00:07:26.750 --> 00:07:29.040
Yeah, it's so easy to pick
out the non-engineers,

00:07:29.040 --> 00:07:29.785
I have to say.

00:07:29.785 --> 00:07:30.454
[LAUGHTER]

00:07:30.454 --> 00:07:32.370
AUDIENCE: I sneaked in
from the same building.

00:07:32.370 --> 00:07:33.203
I work in marketing.

00:07:33.203 --> 00:07:35.150
STEVEN J. DUBNER: OK,
and there was one more?

00:07:35.150 --> 00:07:36.476
Yeah.

00:07:36.476 --> 00:07:38.790
AUDIENCE: I work in editorial.

00:07:38.790 --> 00:07:40.290
STEVEN J. DUBNER:
OK, so a good half

00:07:40.290 --> 00:07:42.500
a percent's smattering of sales,
marketing, and editorial along

00:07:42.500 --> 00:07:43.125
with engineers.

00:07:43.125 --> 00:07:46.310
OK, so I know how you all
spend your day generally.

00:07:46.310 --> 00:07:49.100
I couldn't survive doing
what you do for half a day.

00:07:49.100 --> 00:07:50.860
I have no idea how
to do what you do,

00:07:50.860 --> 00:07:53.110
but I generally understand
what it is you do.

00:07:53.110 --> 00:07:57.355
So let me just tell you
briefly how I spend my day.

00:07:57.355 --> 00:07:59.105
I live in New York in
the Upper West Side.

00:07:59.105 --> 00:08:00.264
I have a nice family.

00:08:00.264 --> 00:08:00.930
I've got a wife.

00:08:00.930 --> 00:08:01.680
I've got two kids.

00:08:01.680 --> 00:08:02.740
I've got a little dog.

00:08:02.740 --> 00:08:07.793
And my office, which is another
apartment near where we live--

00:08:07.793 --> 00:08:09.250
it's about two blocks away.

00:08:09.250 --> 00:08:11.109
So in the morning, I get up.

00:08:11.109 --> 00:08:11.900
I have some coffee.

00:08:11.900 --> 00:08:13.750
I read some papers, say
goodbye to the kids,

00:08:13.750 --> 00:08:16.160
and I go to my office
at about 7:30 AM.

00:08:16.160 --> 00:08:20.220
And I usually walk the dog along
the park, which is very nice.

00:08:20.220 --> 00:08:22.020
And then once I start
my day, all I'm doing

00:08:22.020 --> 00:08:24.170
is I'm walking with the
dog, looking at the park,

00:08:24.170 --> 00:08:25.434
and I'm thinking about stuff.

00:08:25.434 --> 00:08:26.350
I'm looking at people.

00:08:26.350 --> 00:08:28.710
I'm looking at the people
interacting on the street,

00:08:28.710 --> 00:08:31.059
in their cars, and
bikes, and pedestrians,

00:08:31.059 --> 00:08:32.850
and wondering why more
people aren't killed

00:08:32.850 --> 00:08:34.433
on that intersection,
because it seems

00:08:34.433 --> 00:08:36.559
to be a very dangerous one.

00:08:36.559 --> 00:08:38.849
I'm looking at weather,
how people respond to it.

00:08:38.849 --> 00:08:41.140
I'm just thinking about the
way people live their lives

00:08:41.140 --> 00:08:43.460
and how they make their
decisions, stuff like that.

00:08:43.460 --> 00:08:46.230
Then I get to my office,
give the dog some food.

00:08:46.230 --> 00:08:48.600
And then I just sit, and
basically all day long, I just

00:08:48.600 --> 00:08:49.270
keep doing that.

00:08:49.270 --> 00:08:50.470
I sit and think.

00:08:50.470 --> 00:08:51.500
And I read.

00:08:51.500 --> 00:08:52.230
And I write.

00:08:52.230 --> 00:08:55.180
And it's entirely
inconsequential.

00:08:55.180 --> 00:08:57.450
And that's I spend my day.

00:08:57.450 --> 00:09:00.690
So for instance, I
like economics a lot.

00:09:00.690 --> 00:09:02.440
I never really liked
the form of economics

00:09:02.440 --> 00:09:04.110
we study in university so much.

00:09:04.110 --> 00:09:07.820
It felt, for me at least,
overly mathematical, not that

00:09:07.820 --> 00:09:09.530
interesting, not that useful.

00:09:09.530 --> 00:09:11.850
It sounded like the
brightest people

00:09:11.850 --> 00:09:14.120
among the professional
economists

00:09:14.120 --> 00:09:16.800
were divided on the most
important issues of the day.

00:09:16.800 --> 00:09:20.060
In other words, we look to
them to describe the economy,

00:09:20.060 --> 00:09:22.642
to actually tell us how the
macroeconomy really works.

00:09:22.642 --> 00:09:25.100
And it turns out that they're
wrong more often than they're

00:09:25.100 --> 00:09:27.150
right, and that the
best and brightest argue

00:09:27.150 --> 00:09:30.470
with each other constantly
about the most essential facts

00:09:30.470 --> 00:09:31.020
of that.

00:09:31.020 --> 00:09:32.978
So I never really liked
that kind of economics,

00:09:32.978 --> 00:09:36.590
but I like the weirder
kind of economics,

00:09:36.590 --> 00:09:40.610
including that my partner Steve
Levitt has worked on for years.

00:09:40.610 --> 00:09:43.562
I like agricultural
economics, for instance.

00:09:43.562 --> 00:09:45.520
Get some of those journals,
like to read those.

00:09:45.520 --> 00:09:47.600
I grew up on a little
farm in upstate New York.

00:09:47.600 --> 00:09:52.020
And food is one of those things
that I marvel at every day.

00:09:52.020 --> 00:09:55.484
A century ago, it was thought
that we had roughly a billion

00:09:55.484 --> 00:09:56.150
people on Earth.

00:09:56.150 --> 00:09:58.960
It was thought that there's no
way we could support 2 billion.

00:09:58.960 --> 00:10:02.459
There's no way we can grow that
much food for 2 billion people.

00:10:02.459 --> 00:10:04.000
And then after that,
there was no way

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:05.570
we can get to three
or five billion.

00:10:05.570 --> 00:10:08.072
Here we are at seven billion,
more than enough food

00:10:08.072 --> 00:10:08.655
for everybody.

00:10:08.655 --> 00:10:10.488
