00:21:21.176 --> 00:21:22.700
check the textbook afterwards.

00:21:22.700 --> 00:21:26.130
But the principal agent
notion in economics

00:21:26.130 --> 00:21:29.390
argues that when there are
two parties, let's say,

00:21:29.390 --> 00:21:31.060
a principal and
agent, who would seem

00:21:31.060 --> 00:21:33.830
to have their
incentives aligned,

00:21:33.830 --> 00:21:36.500
it's often the case that
they're not aligned for reasons

00:21:36.500 --> 00:21:37.700
that I'll explain right now.

00:21:37.700 --> 00:21:39.307
So let's say in a
police department,

00:21:39.307 --> 00:21:41.390
you would think everybody
in the police department

00:21:41.390 --> 00:21:43.750
wants to arrest people who
are doing crimes, right?

00:21:43.750 --> 00:21:44.920
That's their mission.

00:21:44.920 --> 00:21:52.690
But let's say that the
mayor Chicago tells

00:21:52.690 --> 00:21:55.400
the chief of police
in Chicago, you know,

00:21:55.400 --> 00:21:57.872
we're bidding on the
Olympics and we really

00:21:57.872 --> 00:21:59.080
want to clean up the streets.

00:21:59.080 --> 00:22:02.040
And we need to wipe out the
most obvious prostitution, OK?

00:22:02.040 --> 00:22:04.930
So let's make it a mission
to get rid of the most

00:22:04.930 --> 00:22:06.900
obvious street prostitution.

00:22:06.900 --> 00:22:08.149
So then what happens?

00:22:08.149 --> 00:22:10.190
The chief of police tells
the cops on the street,

00:22:10.190 --> 00:22:10.773
you know what?

00:22:10.773 --> 00:22:13.400
Let's go Arrest a bunch of
prostitutes for a few months

00:22:13.400 --> 00:22:15.100
and just tell them
that they have

00:22:15.100 --> 00:22:18.570
to get off the street for a year
or so, or maybe take it inside

00:22:18.570 --> 00:22:20.190
or whatever.

00:22:20.190 --> 00:22:23.440
So it would seem to be that's
an alignment of incentives.

00:22:23.440 --> 00:22:26.580
Everybody's getting paid to
do the job, which in this case

00:22:26.580 --> 00:22:29.290
is to get prostitutes
off the street.

00:22:29.290 --> 00:22:31.220
But the way the
real world works,

00:22:31.220 --> 00:22:33.620
you often have a
principal agent dilemma,

00:22:33.620 --> 00:22:36.934
which is that the
principal has a clear goal

00:22:36.934 --> 00:22:39.600
and the agent, who's supposed to
be carrying out the principal's

00:22:39.600 --> 00:22:42.420
wishes, seems to have
a clear goal, but then

00:22:42.420 --> 00:22:44.022
personal incentives
come into play.

00:22:44.022 --> 00:22:45.730
Because there are the
personal incentives

00:22:45.730 --> 00:22:48.670
and the public incentives,
or the official incentives.

00:22:48.670 --> 00:22:52.470
So as it turns out,
from the data what

00:22:52.470 --> 00:22:55.550
we learned about this particular
case of the principal agent

00:22:55.550 --> 00:22:59.230
problem was that a given
prostitute in Chicago

00:22:59.230 --> 00:23:01.680
was more likely to
have sex with a cop

00:23:01.680 --> 00:23:04.400
for free than to
be arrested by one.

00:23:04.400 --> 00:23:07.380
In other words, the cops found
it much more to their liking

00:23:07.380 --> 00:23:09.680
not to arrest the
prostitutes and actually

00:23:09.680 --> 00:23:11.790
to take advantage
of them the way

00:23:11.790 --> 00:23:14.170
the customers did,
except, because they

00:23:14.170 --> 00:23:15.910
had the leverage, for free.

00:23:15.910 --> 00:23:19.275
So those are the
kind of findings,

00:23:19.275 --> 00:23:20.900
if you want to call
that, that you just

00:23:20.900 --> 00:23:22.080
can't get without data.

00:23:22.080 --> 00:23:24.970
So we work to get those data.

00:23:24.970 --> 00:23:30.140
And when it comes to education,
and college diplomas,

00:23:30.140 --> 00:23:33.320
and college degrees, we
were interested to know,

00:23:33.320 --> 00:23:37.010
since they're so valuable
and so expensive,

00:23:37.010 --> 00:23:38.400
how many people cheat?

00:23:38.400 --> 00:23:41.075
How many people steal
them in some way, right?

00:23:41.075 --> 00:23:42.450
There are a lot
of different ways

00:23:42.450 --> 00:23:47.444
to cheat to get a college
degree or a diploma.

00:23:47.444 --> 00:23:48.860
So we began looking
into, and it's

00:23:48.860 --> 00:23:52.490
turned out to be really hard to
get any kind of firsthand data.

00:23:52.490 --> 00:23:53.960
The best we could
do, however, was

00:23:53.960 --> 00:23:59.910
an FBI agent who had spent years
doing this, looking into it.

00:23:59.910 --> 00:24:01.204
And he was really good.

00:24:01.204 --> 00:24:02.870
Plus, it helps when
you're with the FBI.

00:24:02.870 --> 00:24:05.770
You can go to the
people who have the data

00:24:05.770 --> 00:24:07.840
and demand that they
give you the data, which

00:24:07.840 --> 00:24:09.880
you and I can't necessarily do.

00:24:09.880 --> 00:24:11.980
And what was really
interesting about this guy is

00:24:11.980 --> 00:24:15.430
he, like a lot of the
people that we write about,

00:24:15.430 --> 00:24:18.010
a lot of the people that I
consider heroes for the way

00:24:18.010 --> 00:24:21.620
that they try to solve
problems, he was motivated by,

00:24:21.620 --> 00:24:24.070
he was driven by a
personal interest.

00:24:24.070 --> 00:24:30.360
And in his case, this was a guy
who was an FBI salaried worker.

00:24:30.360 --> 00:24:31.982
So he's not making
a ton of money.

00:24:31.982 --> 00:24:34.190
And had two daughters getting
ready to go to college.

00:24:34.190 --> 00:24:35.710
He lived in North Carolina.

00:24:35.710 --> 00:24:38.730
And he realized that even if
he sent them to very good state

00:24:38.730 --> 00:24:41.630
colleges, like University of
North Carolina at Chapel Hill,

00:24:41.630 --> 00:24:44.040
that it was going to
cost-- I don't know-- maybe

00:24:44.040 --> 00:24:46.260
$60 to $80,000.

00:24:46.260 --> 00:24:49.920
If you add in everything, maybe
$100,000 for the two daughters

00:24:49.920 --> 00:24:52.540
to get their college degree.

00:24:52.540 --> 00:24:54.520
And the human in him,
not the FBI agent in him,

00:24:54.520 --> 00:24:57.830
the human in him was just
thinking that's a lot of money.

00:24:57.830 --> 00:25:01.040
I wish I could just
buy them a fake diploma

00:25:01.040 --> 00:25:02.590
and buy them a fake degree.

00:25:02.590 --> 00:25:04.850
And I would pay $5,000
or $10,000 for that

00:25:04.850 --> 00:25:09.250
happily if it was good
enough to convince everybody

00:25:09.250 --> 00:25:10.750
that needed convincing.

00:25:10.750 --> 00:25:13.380
So obviously, that's not what
we think of as education.

00:25:13.380 --> 00:25:15.900
That's what we think as just
the outcome of the education.

00:25:15.900 --> 00:25:19.200
But if you think about it, when
you show up to apply for a job,

00:25:19.200 --> 00:25:22.730
they don't really ask-- except
maybe at Google-- what you

00:25:22.730 --> 00:25:24.124
studied in philosophy class.

00:25:24.124 --> 00:25:25.790
They just want to
know that you have it.

00:25:25.790 --> 00:25:28.750
And nobody even ever
asks for the degree.

00:25:28.750 --> 00:25:30.620
So he thought if
I'm willing to pay

00:25:30.620 --> 00:25:33.237
that money for fake
diplomas for my daughters,

00:25:33.237 --> 00:25:34.820
and I'm an FBI agent,
presumably there

00:25:34.820 --> 00:25:37.403
are some other people out there
who would be willing to do it.

00:25:37.403 --> 00:25:41.030
So he begin to explore
the world of diploma mills

00:25:41.030 --> 00:25:42.410
and counterfeit shops.

00:25:42.410 --> 00:25:46.020
So it turns out there are a
lot of different kinds of ways

00:25:46.020 --> 00:25:48.110
to get a fake diploma, or
to make a fake diploma,

00:25:48.110 --> 00:25:49.810
and to market it.

00:25:49.810 --> 00:25:53.180
And the two basic ones
are diploma mills,

00:25:53.180 --> 00:25:57.850
which would be basically like
you could take a correspondence

00:25:57.850 --> 00:26:01.790
course in, like, golf
course maintenance

00:26:01.790 --> 00:26:03.090
from some university.

00:26:03.090 --> 00:26:05.830
And you could then parlay
that one correspondence course

00:26:05.830 --> 00:26:09.570
into a bachelor's degree
for an extra $500 or $1,000.

00:26:09.570 --> 00:26:10.450
OK?

00:26:10.450 --> 00:26:13.040
then So that's the
diploma mill form.

00:26:13.040 --> 00:26:15.240
And then there are
counterfeit shops

00:26:15.240 --> 00:26:18.920
where they can just, basically,
print very, very, very

00:26:18.920 --> 00:26:19.760
good diplomas.

00:26:19.760 --> 00:26:25.070
And the market being what it
is, the price variance is huge.

00:26:25.070 --> 00:26:28.020
But for like about
$5,000 or $6,000

00:26:28.020 --> 00:26:33.360
you could get a beautiful
indistinguishably inauthentic

00:26:33.360 --> 00:26:36.270
medical degree from Harvard
for about $5,000 or $6,000.

00:26:36.270 --> 00:26:37.070
OK?

00:26:37.070 --> 00:26:40.930
So when this agent began
to gather these data,

00:26:40.930 --> 00:26:45.100
arrest these people, find their
sources, find their customers,

00:26:45.100 --> 00:26:47.540
began to measure the customers
against the actual number

00:26:47.540 --> 00:26:51.700
of college graduates, it turned
out that approximately 1%

00:26:51.700 --> 00:26:54.390
of all college degrees awarded
in the United States every year

00:26:54.390 --> 00:26:55.870
were totally fake.

00:26:55.870 --> 00:26:56.445
So 1%.

00:26:56.445 --> 00:26:59.380
So you think 1% of anything
is not necessarily that much,

00:26:59.380 --> 00:27:02.090
except when it's 1% of a big
number like that for whom

00:27:02.090 --> 00:27:04.510
this credential is supposed
to be kind of life altering,

00:27:04.510 --> 00:27:06.510
and for which you're
supposed to have spent four

00:27:06.510 --> 00:27:09.730
to eight years and
maybe $100,000 on,

00:27:09.730 --> 00:27:11.250
it's pretty significant.

00:27:11.250 --> 00:27:15.380
So the bottom line
of that statistic

00:27:15.380 --> 00:27:19.882
is if you work with,
let's say 100 people,

00:27:19.882 --> 00:27:22.506
and how many people are in this
room today would you say, Will?

00:27:22.506 --> 00:27:24.082
[LAUGHTER]

00:27:24.082 --> 00:27:26.290
So I won't point any fingers,
but if you look around,

00:27:26.290 --> 00:27:28.910
the odds are that someone
here is totally piping it in

00:27:28.910 --> 00:27:30.827
and that their diploma
is entirely fictitious.

00:27:30.827 --> 00:27:32.826
Now, it doesn't mean that
that person's actually

00:27:32.826 --> 00:27:34.860
gonna be a worse employee
than the people who

00:27:34.860 --> 00:27:37.900
went to school for the
four years or eight years,

00:27:37.900 --> 00:27:40.270
but that's what the data say.

00:27:40.270 --> 00:27:41.890
This is how I spend my days.

00:27:41.890 --> 00:27:44.760
It's in some ways, I guess,
not that different from yours,

00:27:44.760 --> 00:27:46.870
in some ways fundamentally
very different.

00:27:46.870 --> 00:27:52.370
So I'd love to open it up
to questions now and see

00:27:52.370 --> 00:27:53.872
what you'd like to know.

00:27:53.872 --> 00:27:54.986
MALE SPEAKER: Please raise your
hand if you have a question,

00:27:54.986 --> 00:27:56.069
and wait for a microphone.

00:27:58.494 --> 00:27:59.660
AUDIENCE: Thanks for coming.

00:27:59.660 --> 00:28:01.934
I think it's fascinating,
this interaction

00:28:01.934 --> 00:28:05.301
between the counterfeit diplomas
and the ROI on education

00:28:05.301 --> 00:28:06.263
that you mentioned.

00:28:06.263 --> 00:28:08.710
Is the ROI in the bit of
paper or in the knowledge

00:28:08.710 --> 00:28:10.239
that you get?

00:28:10.239 --> 00:28:11.780
STEVEN J. DUBNER:
That's the question

00:28:11.780 --> 00:28:13.095
no one can answer, honestly.

00:28:17.490 --> 00:28:21.540
If you could come up with
a good way to measure that,

00:28:21.540 --> 00:28:22.890
I'd love to know.

00:28:22.890 --> 00:28:25.300
There are ways you could
imagine measuring it,

00:28:25.300 --> 00:28:29.920
but no one that I've ever
found has actually done that.

00:28:29.920 --> 00:28:34.180
It's not hard to imagine that
the vast majority of the value

00:28:34.180 --> 00:28:38.180
lies in actual knowledge
and skills acquisition,

00:28:38.180 --> 00:28:40.880
but there are those who argue
that a great part of the value

00:28:40.880 --> 00:28:43.870
in a college education lies
in communicative skills,

00:28:43.870 --> 00:28:46.599
networking skills, and so on.

00:28:46.599 --> 00:28:48.890
And if you think about the
cost of a college education,

00:28:48.890 --> 00:28:52.020
both in terms of dollars or
pounds, and in terms of hours,

00:28:52.020 --> 00:28:53.940
which are very, very,
very substantial.

00:28:53.940 --> 00:28:57.670
The people who make the argument
that a lot fewer people should

00:28:57.670 --> 00:29:00.690
go to college, people who make
that argument, their argument

00:29:00.690 --> 00:29:03.090
is that the opportunity
cost is huge.

00:29:03.090 --> 00:29:08.470
So let's say you take
10 students in the UK.

00:29:08.470 --> 00:29:10.430
And in terms of
academic ability,

00:29:10.430 --> 00:29:12.154
you take numbers 4 through 7.

00:29:12.154 --> 00:29:14.320
8 through 10, you say they're
going to a university.

00:29:14.320 --> 00:29:16.366
1 through 3, maybe they're
going to trade school

00:29:16.366 --> 00:29:17.490
or going straight to a job.

00:29:17.490 --> 00:29:19.420
Let's say we take
4 through 7, and we

00:29:19.420 --> 00:29:21.890
have to decide what we're
going to do with them,

00:29:21.890 --> 00:29:23.750
or what would be the
best outcome for them

00:29:23.750 --> 00:29:25.440
personally and for society.

00:29:25.440 --> 00:29:28.030
There are those who would
argue that the opportunity

00:29:28.030 --> 00:29:30.630
cost of college is so huge that
if you took two years or four

00:29:30.630 --> 00:29:33.650
years and the amount of dollars
that are spent and invested

00:29:33.650 --> 00:29:37.000
them in that person, or that
person was able to invest

00:29:37.000 --> 00:29:39.010
him or herself in
a small businesses

00:29:39.010 --> 00:29:42.590
or in other training, that could
far, far increase the output.

00:29:42.590 --> 00:29:48.100
So basically the most nuanced
argument that I think is valid

00:29:48.100 --> 00:29:53.240
is that the way that
college is pitched to

00:29:53.240 --> 00:29:56.880
and positioned for
all students is

00:29:56.880 --> 00:29:59.640
pretty poor for all students, in
that there should be a lot more

00:29:59.640 --> 00:30:01.102
segmentation than there is.

00:30:01.102 --> 00:30:02.060
That's the bottom line.

00:30:02.060 --> 00:30:04.480
So I think you could argue
that for a lot of people

00:30:04.480 --> 00:30:06.760
who go to college expecting
the skills and knowledge

00:30:06.760 --> 00:30:09.740
acquisition to be the thing
that makes them more successful,

00:30:09.740 --> 00:30:11.650
it doesn't happen-- absolutely.

00:30:11.650 --> 00:30:13.930
But we don't know.

00:30:13.930 --> 00:30:15.790
I've never seen
great data on that.

00:30:15.790 --> 00:30:20.099
Even the data, honestly,
on the ROI in college

00:30:20.099 --> 00:30:21.140
are very hard to come by.

00:30:21.140 --> 00:30:25.030
Because if you think about
it, you can't randomize that.

00:30:25.030 --> 00:30:26.490
What you'd want
to do is you want

00:30:26.490 --> 00:30:29.730
to take like 10
cities in the UK,

00:30:29.730 --> 00:30:35.400
and pick 1,000 graduating
students from those cities,

00:30:35.400 --> 00:30:37.340
and randomize them all, right?

00:30:37.340 --> 00:30:40.550
And maybe just do two
groups, maybe do four groups,

00:30:40.550 --> 00:30:43.290
but you send some to
great universities, some

00:30:43.290 --> 00:30:45.390
just out to get
a job, and so on.

00:30:45.390 --> 00:30:47.310
And then you'd
measure the effect

00:30:47.310 --> 00:30:48.670
of the university itself.

00:30:48.670 --> 00:30:50.460
But we can't do that.

00:30:50.460 --> 00:30:52.310
So the best studies
that have been done

00:30:52.310 --> 00:30:54.050
are these natural
experiments, one

00:30:54.050 --> 00:30:57.155
having to do with the military
draft during the Vietnam War

00:30:57.155 --> 00:30:58.530
when there were
a bunch of people

00:30:58.530 --> 00:31:01.110
who would have gone to
college but didn't, and then

00:31:01.110 --> 00:31:04.560
other observationally equivalent
people who did go to college.

00:31:04.560 --> 00:31:08.590
And from that one study and
from some other similar ones,

00:31:08.590 --> 00:31:11.470
the conclusion has been had
that the ROI is gigantic.

00:31:11.470 --> 00:31:18.880
But even then, the answers
are not nearly as foolproof

00:31:18.880 --> 00:31:19.595
as we might wish.

00:31:19.595 --> 00:31:21.678
AUDIENCE: If the alternatives
are going to college

00:31:21.678 --> 00:31:24.105
or going to war, I guess, yeah.

00:31:24.105 --> 00:31:25.480
STEVEN J. DUBNER:
Agreed, agreed.

00:31:25.480 --> 00:31:27.189
Yeah.

