It's going to be
weird sexonomics.

00:33:06.240 --> 00:33:08.160
That can't work.

00:33:08.160 --> 00:33:09.200
It's too long.

00:33:09.200 --> 00:33:10.284
It doesn't mean anything.

00:33:10.284 --> 00:33:11.200
That's what they said.

00:33:11.200 --> 00:33:12.720
It doesn't mean anything.

00:33:12.720 --> 00:33:16.390
And I said, have you ever
heard of a portmanteau?

00:33:16.390 --> 00:33:18.380
People make up words.

00:33:18.380 --> 00:33:22.150
They even make even
make up titles.

00:33:22.150 --> 00:33:23.820
So I made up a word one time.

00:33:26.600 --> 00:33:29.000
I think this is the only
good word I ever made up.

00:33:29.000 --> 00:33:32.270
You know you run into someone
that you used to date,

00:33:32.270 --> 00:33:34.054
and they got married afterwards?

00:33:34.054 --> 00:33:35.720
And you realize you
were the last person

00:33:35.720 --> 00:33:39.282
they dated before they married?

00:33:39.282 --> 00:33:40.490
So what you call that person?

00:33:40.490 --> 00:33:42.950
There should be a
word for it, right?

00:33:42.950 --> 00:33:45.639
OK, try this-- penultimore.

00:33:45.639 --> 00:33:46.138
[LAUGHTER]

00:33:46.138 --> 00:33:46.637
Right?

00:33:49.346 --> 00:33:51.310
So I thought "Freakonomics"
was pretty good.

00:33:51.310 --> 00:33:53.490
And it took the
publisher-- it was

00:33:53.490 --> 00:33:56.827
right up to the 11th
hour of publications,

00:33:56.827 --> 00:33:57.910
and they finally said, OK.

00:33:57.910 --> 00:33:59.080
We'll go with "Freakonomics."

00:33:59.080 --> 00:34:00.293
Then the book came out,
and it did very well.

00:34:00.293 --> 00:34:02.001
And they immediately
claimed total credit

00:34:02.001 --> 00:34:03.485
for having come
up with the title.

00:34:03.485 --> 00:34:04.610
So that was "Freakonomics."

00:34:04.610 --> 00:34:05.840
Then we did "Super
Freakonomics,"

00:34:05.840 --> 00:34:07.010
which was not that
controversial,

00:34:07.010 --> 00:34:08.759
although the publisher,
again, was worried

00:34:08.759 --> 00:34:11.159
that the estate of Rick James
was going to come after us,

00:34:11.159 --> 00:34:12.170
which they did not.

00:34:12.170 --> 00:34:13.711
And then we did
"Think Like a Freak."

00:34:13.711 --> 00:34:16.090
That was actually
pretty agreed upon.

00:34:16.090 --> 00:34:18.730
But this one, think
about the signal

00:34:18.730 --> 00:34:20.572
you're trying to send
with a title, right?

00:34:20.572 --> 00:34:21.280
it's interesting.

00:34:21.280 --> 00:34:24.310
We make the argument that
names don't matter, right?

00:34:24.310 --> 00:34:27.280
But the argument that
titles don't matter

00:34:27.280 --> 00:34:28.310
is much harder to make.

00:34:28.310 --> 00:34:33.030
And the reason is that
the name of a person

00:34:33.030 --> 00:34:35.710
is not marketing in the
same way that a product

00:34:35.710 --> 00:34:37.290
title is marketing, right?

00:34:37.290 --> 00:34:41.330
So if you name something
Google or even ESPN,

00:34:41.330 --> 00:34:44.260
there are people who are
going to hear it repeatedly

00:34:44.260 --> 00:34:47.050
before they start to use
it and learn whether it's

00:34:47.050 --> 00:34:48.510
any good for them and so on.

00:34:48.510 --> 00:34:50.239
But a name is a
little different.

00:34:50.239 --> 00:34:52.098
You hear the name,
you meet the person,

00:34:52.098 --> 00:34:53.139
and you know that person.

00:34:53.139 --> 00:34:54.730
And name becomes secondary.

00:34:54.730 --> 00:34:57.420
It doesn't continue to
serve a marketing function.

00:34:57.420 --> 00:35:01.357
So a book title name
seems to be important.

00:35:01.357 --> 00:35:02.940
Again, it's very
hard to tell. there's

00:35:02.940 --> 00:35:05.200
not a lot of A/B
testing in this realm.

00:35:05.200 --> 00:35:07.580
And for this one, the
book title we came up with

00:35:07.580 --> 00:35:11.560
was drawn from one of the
posts that's in this book.

00:35:11.560 --> 00:35:14.510
And it was called "Hurray
for High Gas Prices."

00:35:14.510 --> 00:35:16.400
So we liked that
because we're American,

00:35:16.400 --> 00:35:18.430
and we talk about gas
prices all the time.

00:35:18.430 --> 00:35:21.070
And there was a
post about peak oil

00:35:21.070 --> 00:35:23.640
this, peak oil that, gas
price is too high, too

00:35:23.640 --> 00:35:25.177
low, the gas tax-- whatever.

00:35:25.177 --> 00:35:27.260
There's a lot I could talk
about with gas and oil.

00:35:27.260 --> 00:35:31.580
But this one posted said
high gas taxes are great,

00:35:31.580 --> 00:35:33.550
because what they
help do is capture

00:35:33.550 --> 00:35:36.860
the cost of this activity
that otherwise isn't

00:35:36.860 --> 00:35:38.560
taxed very well, like water.

00:35:38.560 --> 00:35:40.940
When water is free
for farmers, of course

00:35:40.940 --> 00:35:43.400
they're gonna use it all and
not leave any for downstream.

00:35:43.400 --> 00:35:46.440
So when gas is cheap, of course
people are gonna drive a lot.

00:35:46.440 --> 00:35:49.530
And then that causes congestion,
accident risk, pollution,

00:35:49.530 --> 00:35:50.600
et cetera, et cetera.

00:35:50.600 --> 00:35:52.470
And unless you can
raise the gas tax, which

00:35:52.470 --> 00:35:56.260
federal officials in DC won't
for a variety of reasons,

00:35:56.260 --> 00:35:59.460
then people just drive a lot.

00:35:59.460 --> 00:36:02.150
So the post was called
"Hurray for High Gas Prices."

00:36:02.150 --> 00:36:04.730
So that, our American
publisher said, yeah, great.

00:36:04.730 --> 00:36:07.405
And than the British publisher,
excellent publisher, Penguin,

00:36:07.405 --> 00:36:08.030
got hold of it.

00:36:08.030 --> 00:36:11.280
And they say, well, gas doesn't
mean here what it means there.

00:36:11.280 --> 00:36:13.110
So it'd have to be
"Hurray for High Petrol

00:36:13.110 --> 00:36:14.810
Prices," which
doesn't work at all,

00:36:14.810 --> 00:36:18.000
or it's gonna sound like it's
a book of gastroenterology

00:36:18.000 --> 00:36:19.850
of some kind.

00:36:19.850 --> 00:36:21.490
So then they said,
can you come up

00:36:21.490 --> 00:36:25.096
with a different title
for the British edition.

00:36:25.096 --> 00:36:28.240
And so I say yeah, but
we don't like the idea

00:36:28.240 --> 00:36:31.630
because it's not
fun to write a book

00:36:31.630 --> 00:36:34.220
and want it be called different
things in different places.

00:36:34.220 --> 00:36:39.180
But then we came up with
a title that we absolutely

00:36:39.180 --> 00:36:41.320
loved, which I thought
would be the perfect title

00:36:41.320 --> 00:36:44.550
for the book, which is called
"We were Only Trying to Help."

00:36:44.550 --> 00:36:45.050
Right?

00:36:45.050 --> 00:36:45.550
[LAUGHTER]

00:36:45.550 --> 00:36:46.930
Isn't that good?

00:36:46.930 --> 00:36:49.460
Because a lot of the
blog posts in this book

00:36:49.460 --> 00:36:53.220
are basically where we just
run an idea of the flag pole.

00:36:53.220 --> 00:36:55.690
Maybe it's about paying
politicians more.

00:36:55.690 --> 00:36:57.230
Maybe it's about gas prices.

00:36:57.230 --> 00:36:59.195
Maybe it's about
proposing a sex tax.

00:36:59.195 --> 00:37:01.570
All these different kinds of
things, knowing that they're

00:37:01.570 --> 00:37:04.590
either not fully enactable
at all, or even a little bit

00:37:04.590 --> 00:37:07.550
enactable, or just
a question to ask

00:37:07.550 --> 00:37:09.550
to get a different kind
of conversation started.

00:37:09.550 --> 00:37:14.380
Because my frustration is that,
politics being what they are,

00:37:14.380 --> 00:37:17.080
institutional
inertia being what it

00:37:17.080 --> 00:37:19.470
is, institutional habits
being what they are,

00:37:19.470 --> 00:37:22.730
it's really really, really
hard to make any real change.

00:37:22.730 --> 00:37:24.390
I mean, change in
most institutions

00:37:24.390 --> 00:37:27.150
is two degrees this
way, when really

00:37:27.150 --> 00:37:29.340
if you look at health
care, education, sometimes

00:37:29.340 --> 00:37:31.510
you need like 90
degrees or 180 degrees.

00:37:31.510 --> 00:37:34.110
So a lot of what we
do is just proposing

00:37:34.110 --> 00:37:36.260
these kind of outlandish ideas.

00:37:36.260 --> 00:37:39.200
One post was Steve
Levitt wrote one

00:37:39.200 --> 00:37:42.400
saying that terrorism
is a concern in the US,

00:37:42.400 --> 00:37:44.400
even though incidents are
very, very, very rare.

00:37:44.400 --> 00:37:46.720
But we're spending a lot of
money, a lot of mindshare

00:37:46.720 --> 00:37:47.290
on it.

00:37:47.290 --> 00:37:48.789
So if we're really
serious about it,

00:37:48.789 --> 00:37:50.780
we should try to think
of all potential ways

00:37:50.780 --> 00:37:52.180
that a terrorists could attack.

00:37:52.180 --> 00:37:55.160
So on the blog, he wrote
asking, dear readers,

00:37:55.160 --> 00:37:57.539
if you were a terrorist,
how would you attack?

00:37:57.539 --> 00:37:59.580
Which seemed like a really
good idea at the time.

00:37:59.580 --> 00:38:00.800
We were only trying to help.

00:38:00.800 --> 00:38:02.550
But as it turns out,
"The New York Times,"

00:38:02.550 --> 00:38:05.270
which was then running
our blog, immediately

00:38:05.270 --> 00:38:07.400
panicked, and shut down
comments, and, I think,

00:38:07.400 --> 00:38:08.469
called the FBI on us.

00:38:08.469 --> 00:38:09.052
It was brutal.

00:38:09.052 --> 00:38:10.757
[LAUGHTER]

00:38:10.757 --> 00:38:12.590
So "We Were Only Trying
to Help" was a title

00:38:12.590 --> 00:38:14.920
that we proposed to
the British publisher.

00:38:14.920 --> 00:38:16.960
And the immediate response
was yeah, perfect.

00:38:16.960 --> 00:38:19.255
And that's why I love our
British publisher so much.

00:38:19.255 --> 00:38:21.630
And then I said to the American
publisher, you know what?

00:38:21.630 --> 00:38:26.090
We got a better title than
"Hurray for High Gas Prices."

00:38:26.090 --> 00:38:27.340
"We Were Only Trying to Help."

00:38:27.340 --> 00:38:28.429
And our editor said, yeah.

00:38:28.429 --> 00:38:28.970
That's great.

00:38:28.970 --> 00:38:29.960
That's awesome.

00:38:29.960 --> 00:38:32.160
And then like three weeks
later, on the same day,

00:38:32.160 --> 00:38:33.990
I get a call from
both publishers.

00:38:33.990 --> 00:38:37.310
Because the way it works now in
publishing, the editorial team,

00:38:37.310 --> 00:38:40.300
and even the marketing team,
and the PR team, no offense,

00:38:40.300 --> 00:38:41.300
they have zero leverage.

00:38:41.300 --> 00:38:43.925
It's a little bit like probably
around here where the engineers

00:38:43.925 --> 00:38:45.260
have all the juice, right?

00:38:45.260 --> 00:38:49.390
So in publishing, sales
has all the juice, right?

00:38:49.390 --> 00:38:52.010
So it's the sales team
will take a book, title,

00:38:52.010 --> 00:38:54.580
and cover out to the
book stores, the chains,

00:38:54.580 --> 00:38:55.997
and Amazons, and so on.

00:38:55.997 --> 00:38:58.080
And they'll say, this is
a new book by these guys.

00:38:58.080 --> 00:39:01.245
And then one person at
the book chain will say,

00:39:01.245 --> 00:39:02.510
I don't like that.

00:39:02.510 --> 00:39:03.740
That sounds stupid.

00:39:03.740 --> 00:39:07.390
Or that sounds like they're
being self-flagellating

00:39:07.390 --> 00:39:08.150
or something.

00:39:08.150 --> 00:39:10.358
So on the same day, I got
a from both publishers that

00:39:10.358 --> 00:39:12.880
said sorry, "We Were Only
Trying to Help" won't work.

00:39:12.880 --> 00:39:16.330
So then we just had to
go looking for a title.

00:39:16.330 --> 00:39:19.650
And we went looking
in the posts that we'd

00:39:19.650 --> 00:39:21.310
selected for the book.

00:39:21.310 --> 00:39:23.610
And one post that we
liked a lot was this one

00:39:23.610 --> 00:39:24.830
called "When to Rob a Bank."

00:39:24.830 --> 00:39:26.788
And the reason we liked
it was because it's not

00:39:26.788 --> 00:39:29.505
about how to rob a bank,
which is kind of procedural.

00:39:29.505 --> 00:39:31.630
It's not about why to rob
a bank, which is obvious.

00:39:31.630 --> 00:39:32.600
It's about when.

00:39:32.600 --> 00:39:35.140
And that's the kind of
question that we like to ask,

00:39:35.140 --> 00:39:38.210
which is if you're gonna do
this, this thing that turns out

00:39:38.210 --> 00:39:39.410
to be pretty stupid.

00:39:39.410 --> 00:39:42.150
So it turns out the
biggest point of this post

00:39:42.150 --> 00:39:45.290
is that the ROI on bank
robbery is just dreadful.

00:39:45.290 --> 00:39:48.609
In Britain, you take
home about, I think,

00:39:48.609 --> 00:39:50.650
two and a half or three
times the amount of money

00:39:50.650 --> 00:39:52.780
you get from an average
bank robbery in the States,

00:39:52.780 --> 00:39:53.655
which is interesting.

00:39:53.655 --> 00:39:56.000
I think it has to do with
just more cash on hand.

00:39:56.000 --> 00:39:59.130
But the rate of arrest, the risk
of arrest is about the same.

00:39:59.130 --> 00:40:01.420
So you're likely to get
arrested after just three bank

00:40:01.420 --> 00:40:01.940
robberies.

00:40:01.940 --> 00:40:05.192
So even if you take
on 10,000 pounds,

00:40:05.192 --> 00:40:06.650
you get arrested
after three times.

00:40:06.650 --> 00:40:12.000
So for 30,000 quid, you're going
to spent a few years in prison.

00:40:12.000 --> 00:40:13.930
And so the ROI is dreadful.

00:40:13.930 --> 00:40:15.890
If you really want
to rob a bank,

00:40:15.890 --> 00:40:19.320
mornings are much
better than afternoons.

00:40:19.320 --> 00:40:21.410
And yet, the vast
majority of bank robbers

00:40:21.410 --> 00:40:24.560
work in the afternoons,
which indicates clearly they

00:40:24.560 --> 00:40:25.790
haven't looked up the data.

00:40:25.790 --> 00:40:27.260
Because if they had,
they'd be working mornings.

00:40:27.260 --> 00:40:29.320
But maybe they just can't
get up in the mornings.

00:40:29.320 --> 00:40:30.310
Maybe they're not
morning risers,

00:40:30.310 --> 00:40:32.351
which is probably why
they're having to rob banks

00:40:32.351 --> 00:40:33.384
in the first place.

00:40:33.384 --> 00:40:35.800
And the very most interesting
part of "When to Rob a Bank"

00:40:35.800 --> 00:40:37.570
for me was that this
was all inspired

00:40:37.570 --> 00:40:41.680
by the story of a woman
in Iowa who was embezzling

00:40:41.680 --> 00:40:43.500
from the bank where she worked.

00:40:43.500 --> 00:40:46.480
And it turned out to be a
bank owned by her father,

00:40:46.480 --> 00:40:48.920
or run by her father.

00:40:48.920 --> 00:40:52.070
So if you're gonna rob a bank,
rob it from inside, right?

00:40:52.070 --> 00:40:54.300
They said the best way to
rob a bank is to own one

00:40:54.300 --> 00:40:55.665
or at least to work at one.

00:40:55.665 --> 00:40:57.540
But what was interesting
about this woman was

00:40:57.540 --> 00:41:00.310
she had been working at
this bank for many years,

00:41:00.310 --> 00:41:01.980
15 or 20 years.

00:41:01.980 --> 00:41:06.070
And she was finally
caught because she

00:41:06.070 --> 00:41:08.850
got so burnt out and
exhausted that she

00:41:08.850 --> 00:41:09.940
had to take some time off.

00:41:09.940 --> 00:41:12.300
And then they discovered
that she'd been keeping

00:41:12.300 --> 00:41:13.539
two sets of books all along.

00:41:13.539 --> 00:41:15.580
And she's embezzled, I
believe, about $2 million.

00:41:15.580 --> 00:41:17.570
And this was in the
1960s, so that was a lot.

00:41:17.570 --> 00:41:19.900
Again, from her father's bank.

00:41:19.900 --> 00:41:21.557
And as it turns out,
the way that she

00:41:21.557 --> 00:41:23.140
had covered it for
all these years was

00:41:23.140 --> 00:41:26.040
by keeping two sets of
books, but by never taking

00:41:26.040 --> 00:41:28.750
a single vacation day,
which is how she got so

00:41:28.750 --> 00:41:30.850
exhausted that she
finally broke down.

00:41:30.850 --> 00:41:33.240
So after she served
her time in prison,

00:41:33.240 --> 00:41:34.530
her parents took her back.

00:41:34.530 --> 00:41:35.920
They were very forgiving.

00:41:35.920 --> 00:41:38.990
And then the FBI or some
law enforcement agency

00:41:38.990 --> 00:41:41.879
said do you want to come
help us catch embezzlers?

00:41:41.879 --> 00:41:43.920
And one of the things that
she introduced them to

00:41:43.920 --> 00:41:46.310
was the notion that
one of the best metrics

00:41:46.310 --> 00:41:49.220
to identify in looking
for embezzlement

00:41:49.220 --> 00:41:54.849
is extraordinary vacation
or sick time pay.

00:41:54.849 --> 00:41:57.390
Because if you're not taking it
either when everybody else is

00:41:57.390 --> 00:41:59.070
taking it, or not
taking it all, it's

00:41:59.070 --> 00:42:01.710
almost certainly because you're
doing something with your books

00:42:01.710 --> 00:42:03.168
that you don't want
anybody to see.

00:42:03.168 --> 00:42:06.184
So that's when to rob a bank.

