In cities that were
growing, they'd

00:43:27.570 --> 00:43:28.150
have a lot of horse manure.

00:43:28.150 --> 00:43:29.858
In the cities, they'd
sell it to farmers,

00:43:29.858 --> 00:43:32.200
but then there was a horse
manure glut as cities grew.

00:43:32.200 --> 00:43:35.420
So London and New York were
paralyzed by horse manure

00:43:35.420 --> 00:43:36.736
because of the economic glut.

00:43:36.736 --> 00:43:38.860
There was so much of it
that they couldn't sell it.

00:43:38.860 --> 00:43:40.860
But then the car came along.

00:43:40.860 --> 00:43:42.390
There are many fewer horses.

00:43:42.390 --> 00:43:44.100
And now horse manure
is quite expensive.

00:43:44.100 --> 00:43:45.640
So that's a case.

00:43:45.640 --> 00:43:50.422
The other instances, there
was spent nuclear fuel.

00:43:50.422 --> 00:43:51.880
So there are some
nuclear engineers

00:43:51.880 --> 00:43:53.963
who figured out how to
make nuclear power by using

00:43:53.963 --> 00:43:55.310
what we call spent fuel.

00:43:55.310 --> 00:43:57.060
And then one example
was chicken feet,

00:43:57.060 --> 00:43:59.150
or what they call in the
industry chicken paws.

00:43:59.150 --> 00:44:02.790
So in the States, almost nobody
eats the feet of chicken.

00:44:02.790 --> 00:44:04.030
Do you eat them here at all?

00:44:04.030 --> 00:44:05.904
So if you go to certain
Chinese restaurants--

00:44:05.904 --> 00:44:09.807
and they look like
this, really clawy.

00:44:09.807 --> 00:44:11.640
And there's that one
spur that's right here.

00:44:11.640 --> 00:44:14.280
They look very much
like a human hand

00:44:14.280 --> 00:44:17.940
was tortured-- a
little bit smaller.

00:44:17.940 --> 00:44:20.090
And they are definitely
an acquired taste.

00:44:20.090 --> 00:44:22.100
I mean, I guess they're
an acquired taste.

00:44:22.100 --> 00:44:24.225
And very few people in
the States eat them,

00:44:24.225 --> 00:44:25.540
and obviously here.

00:44:25.540 --> 00:44:27.440
But in China, they're huge.

00:44:27.440 --> 00:44:32.240
So it used to be that chicken
producing firms in the US

00:44:32.240 --> 00:44:35.610
would throw away
billions of chicken feet

00:44:35.610 --> 00:44:38.350
every year at great cost.

00:44:38.350 --> 00:44:41.200
And then as they begin to
do more global business,

00:44:41.200 --> 00:44:44.320
it turns out that they would
sell a whole lot to Asia.

00:44:44.320 --> 00:44:49.330
And now big chicken producing
companies like Purdue

00:44:49.330 --> 00:44:52.760
tell me that they
would not be profitable

00:44:52.760 --> 00:44:54.940
were it not for the
sale of chicken paws,

00:44:54.940 --> 00:44:57.200
that that's how close
the margins are,

00:44:57.200 --> 00:45:00.130
and chicken paws put
them over the top.

00:45:00.130 --> 00:45:02.980
That said, in the States
and here, the taste

00:45:02.980 --> 00:45:05.030
is plainly for the white
meat of chicken as well.

00:45:05.030 --> 00:45:06.654
So I'm guessing that
what you would see

00:45:06.654 --> 00:45:10.426
is that there are some chickens
that are bred for that,

00:45:10.426 --> 00:45:11.800
and that among
those, there might

00:45:11.800 --> 00:45:12.925
be artificial insemination.

00:45:12.925 --> 00:45:16.380
But I don't know enough about
bird reproductive-- I should

00:45:16.380 --> 00:45:18.142
now, but yes, I don't know.

00:45:18.142 --> 00:45:19.500
That's a good question.

00:45:19.500 --> 00:45:21.794
Yes, anyone else?

00:45:21.794 --> 00:45:24.550
MALE SPEAKER: Could
you pass the mic over?

00:45:24.550 --> 00:45:25.900
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:45:25.900 --> 00:45:27.655
So why are politicians
so resistant

00:45:27.655 --> 00:45:30.390
to evidence-based policymaking?

00:45:30.390 --> 00:45:32.830
STEVEN J. DUBNER: Why are
they so resistant to what?

00:45:32.830 --> 00:45:34.413
AUDIENCE: Evidence
based policymaking.

00:45:34.413 --> 00:45:35.760
STEVEN J. DUBNER: Oh.

00:45:35.760 --> 00:45:39.810
Well, before I join with
you in accusing them,

00:45:39.810 --> 00:45:41.430
let me defend them for a minute.

00:45:41.430 --> 00:45:47.792
Why is everybody averse to
evidence-based decision making?

00:45:47.792 --> 00:45:49.625
I'll just give you two
very quick parallels.

00:45:53.950 --> 00:45:55.544
I'm just going to guess here.

00:45:55.544 --> 00:45:57.710
A bunch of people sitting
here are Google engineers.

00:45:57.710 --> 00:46:00.974
I'm guessing probably
at least 5% of you

00:46:00.974 --> 00:46:04.730
have a parent who's
a doctor, an MD.

00:46:04.730 --> 00:46:07.570
raise your hand if you
have a parent who's an MD.

00:46:07.570 --> 00:46:08.070
OK.

00:46:08.070 --> 00:46:10.870
That's about right.

00:46:10.870 --> 00:46:14.633
So medicine is fascinating.

00:46:17.789 --> 00:46:19.830
There's so much be grateful
for and thankful for,

00:46:19.830 --> 00:46:21.780
but it's also very,
very frustrating.

00:46:21.780 --> 00:46:24.580
Because even though there's
a lot of science in it,

00:46:24.580 --> 00:46:28.600
most doctors aren't
remotely scientific.

00:46:28.600 --> 00:46:30.760
And it turns out that
most doctors are also

00:46:30.760 --> 00:46:34.510
terrible with data, that they're
unbelievably bad with the most

00:46:34.510 --> 00:46:36.130
basic sets of probabilities.

00:46:36.130 --> 00:46:37.544
Many doctors are, at least.

00:46:37.544 --> 00:46:39.710
And then when they communicate
it to their patients,

00:46:39.710 --> 00:46:42.840
it gets even worse, because it
becomes a game of telephone,

00:46:42.840 --> 00:46:50.960
whereas you have a 2% chance
within 10 years of developing

00:46:50.960 --> 00:46:54.250
a potentially fatal condition.

00:46:54.250 --> 00:46:56.500
And many people hear that
in many different ways,

00:46:56.500 --> 00:46:58.080
but a lot of people
hear it in a way

00:46:58.080 --> 00:47:01.335
that nobody who knows any
statistics would ever embrace.

00:47:03.920 --> 00:47:06.680
So doctors, I always
grew up thinking,

00:47:06.680 --> 00:47:09.072
were scientific in the way
that we think of scientific,

00:47:09.072 --> 00:47:10.780
meaning the scientific
method, and things

00:47:10.780 --> 00:47:12.170
are tried and proven.

00:47:12.170 --> 00:47:13.090
There are hypotheses.

00:47:13.090 --> 00:47:14.230
There's data gathered and so on.

00:47:14.230 --> 00:47:16.230
And it turns out that
most medicine isn't really

00:47:16.230 --> 00:47:17.060
built that way.

00:47:17.060 --> 00:47:18.518
And the only medicine
that's really

00:47:18.518 --> 00:47:22.100
build that way these
days is pharmaceuticals

00:47:22.100 --> 00:47:24.800
and some forms of
medical interventions,

00:47:24.800 --> 00:47:26.140
actual treatments.

00:47:26.140 --> 00:47:28.400
But the vast
majority of it is not

00:47:28.400 --> 00:47:31.710
what you would really
call evidence-based.

00:47:31.710 --> 00:47:34.320
And that's a pretty scary
thought at the end of the day.

00:47:34.320 --> 00:47:36.460
And so we've done stories
recently in our podcast,

00:47:36.460 --> 00:47:40.960
again, where even when there are
evidence-based proofs of sorts

00:47:40.960 --> 00:47:44.200
of treatment or in the
realm of medical health care

00:47:44.200 --> 00:47:49.400
delivery that's known to
be efficient, even then,

00:47:49.400 --> 00:47:51.980
policymakers aren't
crazy about adopting it.

00:47:51.980 --> 00:47:56.140
So there's this one case we
did a podcast about in Camden,

00:47:56.140 --> 00:47:58.590
New Jersey that's a very,
very labor intensive,

00:47:58.590 --> 00:48:02.170
cost intensive intervention,
where turns out it in this area

00:48:02.170 --> 00:48:06.400
but in many geographical areas,
roughly 5% of the medical

00:48:06.400 --> 00:48:09.330
patients are responsible for
consuming about 50$ of all

00:48:09.330 --> 00:48:12.110
health care costs
of all health care.

00:48:12.110 --> 00:48:14.810
So it's a huge,
huge, huge problem.

00:48:14.810 --> 00:48:17.590
You've just got
massive concentration

00:48:17.590 --> 00:48:20.810
among people who are going to
the emergency room 100 times

00:48:20.810 --> 00:48:22.900
a year, just consuming
all kinds of cost.

00:48:22.900 --> 00:48:25.160
So these people came
up with the thought

00:48:25.160 --> 00:48:27.260
what if we, instead of
treating things the way

00:48:27.260 --> 00:48:30.050
we are now, which
is terribly, what

00:48:30.050 --> 00:48:34.230
if we come up with a new plan
to invent a social services

00:48:34.230 --> 00:48:37.100
multifaceted network where
we offer medical care

00:48:37.100 --> 00:48:40.350
but we also offer counseling
so people actually understand

00:48:40.350 --> 00:48:42.259
what drugs they're
supposed to take and when,

00:48:42.259 --> 00:48:44.050
so we actually help
them get to the doctors

00:48:44.050 --> 00:48:45.350
they're supposed to go to.

00:48:45.350 --> 00:48:47.170
So if they need to go to drug
rehab, they're doing that,

00:48:47.170 --> 00:48:47.870
and so on.

00:48:47.870 --> 00:48:50.820
So an expensive,
hands-on project

00:48:50.820 --> 00:48:53.270
that ended up being very
effective and very cost

00:48:53.270 --> 00:48:55.240
effective, considering
what it saved.

00:48:55.240 --> 00:48:58.300
So even after this kind
of thing is proven,

00:48:58.300 --> 00:49:01.690
no one in the federal
government associated

00:49:01.690 --> 00:49:03.620
with Medicare and
Medicaid, I'm told,

00:49:03.620 --> 00:49:04.990
really wanted to have
anything to do with it.

00:49:04.990 --> 00:49:06.510
Because the
constituencies are just

00:49:06.510 --> 00:49:09.550
so large and ingrained that
they really couldn't make any

00:49:09.550 --> 00:49:10.180
persuasions.

00:49:10.180 --> 00:49:13.660
So in health care,
evidence-based medicine

00:49:13.660 --> 00:49:16.170
is still more of a dream.

00:49:16.170 --> 00:49:20.550
In education,
evidence-based curricula

00:49:20.550 --> 00:49:22.660
are only beginning
to come online.

00:49:22.660 --> 00:49:25.860
So for politicians,
I would argue, yeah,

00:49:25.860 --> 00:49:27.540
they're particularly
visible in the way

00:49:27.540 --> 00:49:29.220
that they fail to
embrace evidence,

00:49:29.220 --> 00:49:32.820
but I don't think they're
very unique at all.

00:49:32.820 --> 00:49:36.950
And why they don't do it is
because, I think, that most

00:49:36.950 --> 00:49:40.210
politicians--
unfortunately, it's

00:49:40.210 --> 00:49:42.130
a principal agent
problem in a way.

00:49:42.130 --> 00:49:44.790
They're the agents and
we're the principals.

00:49:44.790 --> 00:49:46.082
So we're the voters.

00:49:46.082 --> 00:49:48.540
We want to problems solved that
we think government is best

00:49:48.540 --> 00:49:49.360
suited to solve.

00:49:49.360 --> 00:49:52.240
And these are typically
long term, complex scenarios

00:49:52.240 --> 00:49:54.870
with a lot of different
players-- transportation,

00:49:54.870 --> 00:49:57.580
health care, education-- things
like this-- geopolitics--

00:49:57.580 --> 00:50:00.430
that individuals can't do,
that businesses, private firms

00:50:00.430 --> 00:50:01.740
don't necessarily do that well.

00:50:01.740 --> 00:50:04.115
So we think, well, this is
what governments are gonna do,

00:50:04.115 --> 00:50:06.924
and that's what we want
our politicians to do.

00:50:06.924 --> 00:50:08.340
And that's what
we elect them for.

00:50:08.340 --> 00:50:09.715
But then once they
get in office,

00:50:09.715 --> 00:50:13.140
the way the system is set up
in democracies at least is that

00:50:13.140 --> 00:50:16.500
they are encouraged to respond
to different incentives,

00:50:16.500 --> 00:50:18.720
which is short term
self-interested incentives

00:50:18.720 --> 00:50:21.676
of getting elected, raising
money, consolidating power,

00:50:21.676 --> 00:50:24.050
getting on the right committee,
consolidating more power,

00:50:24.050 --> 00:50:27.180
raising more money in order
to perpetuate their own--

00:50:27.180 --> 00:50:29.600
So even though we don't
like it-- We hate that.

00:50:29.600 --> 00:50:30.760
We all hate that.

00:50:30.760 --> 00:50:32.900
But for me, it's hard
to blame them for it,

00:50:32.900 --> 00:50:34.600
because that's the
set of incentives

00:50:34.600 --> 00:50:36.360
that they walked into.

00:50:36.360 --> 00:50:38.770
There are a few maybe
idealistic people who buck it,

00:50:38.770 --> 00:50:40.765
but very few people's
ideology is really

00:50:40.765 --> 00:50:43.056
as strong as the incentives
that they're responding to.

00:50:43.056 --> 00:50:45.410
So one solution to this
that we've proposed,

00:50:45.410 --> 00:50:47.730
I think, in this book,
in "When to Rob a Bank,"

00:50:47.730 --> 00:50:49.771
and I've talked about this
with many politicians.

00:50:49.771 --> 00:50:51.730
And they always nod and smile.

00:50:51.730 --> 00:50:52.530
They say, oh yeah.

00:50:52.530 --> 00:50:54.190
Great, great, great idea.

00:50:54.190 --> 00:50:56.300
But at the end of
the day, they hate it

00:50:56.300 --> 00:50:58.400
because it's totally possible.

00:50:58.400 --> 00:51:01.520
The idea would be A,
we should probably

00:51:01.520 --> 00:51:03.830
try at least, we should
experiment with paying

00:51:03.830 --> 00:51:06.660
politicians a lot more.

00:51:06.660 --> 00:51:09.812
So how many parliamentary
districts are there in the UK?

00:51:09.812 --> 00:51:10.960
AUDIENCE: 625.

00:51:10.960 --> 00:51:12.099
STEVEN J. DUBNER: 625?

00:51:12.099 --> 00:51:14.140
So it would be really fun
to take that, divide it

00:51:14.140 --> 00:51:17.280
in two or four, randomize,
and raise the sal-- what's

00:51:17.280 --> 00:51:18.100
an MP get paid?

00:51:18.100 --> 00:51:19.270
100,000 a year or something?

00:51:19.270 --> 00:51:20.042
[LAUGHTER]

00:51:20.042 --> 00:51:21.250
STEVEN J. DUBNER: OH, really?

00:51:21.250 --> 00:51:22.510
AUDIENCE: About 80, I think.

00:51:22.510 --> 00:51:23.410
STEVEN J. DUBNER: 70,000 pounds?

00:51:23.410 --> 00:51:24.035
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:51:24.035 --> 00:51:27.750
STEVEN J. DUBNER: So $100,000--
70,000 pounds, we'll say.

00:51:27.750 --> 00:51:30.050
It would be really fun
to take an experiment.

00:51:30.050 --> 00:51:33.560
So for five years, in two
districts, we leave it.

00:51:33.560 --> 00:51:35.530
In one district, we have it.

00:51:35.530 --> 00:51:37.530
In one set of districts,
rather, we do this.

00:51:37.530 --> 00:51:39.390
And in one set of
districts, we double it.

00:51:39.390 --> 00:51:41.540
All you're really
looking for, initially,

00:51:41.540 --> 00:51:45.410
is do higher salaries attract
a different kind of person

00:51:45.410 --> 00:51:46.630
to go into politics?

00:51:46.630 --> 00:51:50.320
So some empirical work that
has been done on this already.

00:51:50.320 --> 00:51:51.650
The answer's yes.

00:51:51.650 --> 00:51:53.550
So in some place
in South America,

00:51:53.550 --> 00:51:55.970
I believe in Mexico--
in Singapore,

00:51:55.970 --> 00:51:57.180
they pay politicians a lot.

00:51:57.180 --> 00:51:58.846
There's a lot of
things that some people

00:51:58.846 --> 00:52:00.010
don't like about Singapore.

00:52:00.010 --> 00:52:01.760
Most political
observers, however,

00:52:01.760 --> 00:52:05.220
argue that it's easily
one of the most efficient,

00:52:05.220 --> 00:52:09.520
uncorrupted, and practical
federal governments out there,

00:52:09.520 --> 00:52:12.780
one reason being-- not
all-- being that they make

00:52:12.780 --> 00:52:14.100
the job incredibly attractive.

00:52:14.100 --> 00:52:16.770
So rather than maybe coming
to Google for a career,

00:52:16.770 --> 00:52:18.510
the same person
might actually want

00:52:18.510 --> 00:52:21.550
to go into council election
or a parliamentary election.

00:52:21.550 --> 00:52:22.740
So that's one.

00:52:22.740 --> 00:52:25.440
You could explore
the idea of changing

00:52:25.440 --> 00:52:28.510
the status of
political jobs, just

00:52:28.510 --> 00:52:30.886
the way we explore changing
the status of teachers,

00:52:30.886 --> 00:52:32.760
which we haven't done
yet either, by the way.

00:52:32.760 --> 00:52:33.470
But that's one idea.

00:52:33.470 --> 00:52:35.050
But then here's the
bigger, bolder one

00:52:35.050 --> 00:52:36.360
that will never,
ever, ever happen,

00:52:36.360 --> 00:52:38.151
but what I think could
really, really work.

00:52:40.850 --> 00:52:42.550
If the problem is
as I described,

00:52:42.550 --> 00:52:45.130
which is that their incentives
are not aligned with ours,

00:52:45.130 --> 00:52:47.380
because they have short
term, self-interested ones,

00:52:47.380 --> 00:52:49.600
we have long term
public-interested ones.

00:52:49.600 --> 00:52:51.840
Well, what if we try
to align them better?

00:52:51.840 --> 00:52:53.550
And one way to align
them better would

00:52:53.550 --> 00:52:57.130
be to remunerate them based
on their achievements,

00:52:57.130 --> 00:52:58.880
merit-based pay, right?

00:52:58.880 --> 00:53:01.450
So right now, if
think about it, how

00:53:01.450 --> 00:53:04.690
does a politician build
up capitol, or build up

00:53:04.690 --> 00:53:05.870
value in their careers?

00:53:05.870 --> 00:53:10.809
By being more visible, by
being usually safe, right?

00:53:10.809 --> 00:53:12.850
So that they're gonna turn
their political career

00:53:12.850 --> 00:53:18.094
into a lobbying, or consulting
career, or whatever afterwards.

00:53:18.094 --> 00:53:19.510
But what we really
want them to do

00:53:19.510 --> 00:53:21.765
is be working on those
transportation, and education,

00:53:21.765 --> 00:53:24.040
and health care problems
that we sent them to do.

00:53:24.040 --> 00:53:26.880
So what if we were to pay
them for doing those problems,

00:53:26.880 --> 00:53:28.470
and pay them a lot?

00:53:28.470 --> 00:53:32.070
So let's say that there's
a Department of Education.

00:53:32.070 --> 00:53:35.965
And we decide that-- I saw that
your British math students,

00:53:35.965 --> 00:53:37.340
you're even worse
than Americans.

00:53:37.340 --> 00:53:38.840
You're terrible, right?

00:53:38.840 --> 00:53:41.270
Where do you find
engineers in this country?

00:53:41.270 --> 00:53:42.060
Right?

00:53:42.060 --> 00:53:43.769
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] British.

00:53:43.769 --> 00:53:45.560
STEVEN J. DUBNER: So
your math scores-- OK,

00:53:45.560 --> 00:53:48.860
so let's say that the
goal for the next 20 years

00:53:48.860 --> 00:53:55.210
is for British school math
scores to rise 15% or 10%

00:53:55.210 --> 00:53:57.849
against international
averages, whatever.

00:53:57.849 --> 00:53:59.390
AUDIENCE: Make the
tests easier then.

00:53:59.390 --> 00:54:01.514
STEVEN J. DUBNER: OK, well,
that's a good solution.

00:54:01.514 --> 00:54:04.060
That's a very political
solution, certainly.

00:54:04.060 --> 00:54:07.029
So immediately I know you'd
be an excellent politician,

00:54:07.029 --> 00:54:09.570
because you would have a very
cheap, effective solution right

00:54:09.570 --> 00:54:10.280
out of the gate.

00:54:10.280 --> 00:54:12.720
So let's say that
that's your goal.

00:54:12.720 --> 00:54:14.790
Then let's set up
a project to try

00:54:14.790 --> 00:54:17.040
to figure out how to get to
that goal with measurables

00:54:17.040 --> 00:54:17.998
with all along the way.

00:54:17.998 --> 00:54:21.307
And you declare somebody
the arbiter of these goals

00:54:21.307 --> 00:54:22.140
and the measurables.

00:54:22.140 --> 00:54:24.970
So maybe it's an
accounting firm, whoever.

00:54:24.970 --> 00:54:26.170
We know how to do that.

00:54:26.170 --> 00:54:28.210
